      "index": "bPm",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1791942245,
      "version": 649,
      "versionNonce": 994834658,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772802054918,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "there are two command top and htop. htop is nothing but the fancy version of top it shows output in fancy\nand detailed way, \nway of seeing the output of top, we will focus on top, we will know htop automatically\n\n\ntop -> with top commands, which process at the very moment is with our processor or is\n    being executed by our processor\n    \n    what thing we need to focus here?\n        \n    first of all if we see any process that is consuming heavy CPU or heavy memory that\n    is something that we can focus from here. we can find the pid and we can kill the \n    process",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "there are two command top and htop. htop is nothing but the fancy version of top it shows output in fancy\nand detailed way, \nway of seeing the output of top, we will focus on top, we will know htop automatically\n\n\ntop -> with top commands, which process at the very moment is with our processor or is\n    being executed by our processor\n    \n    what thing we need to focus here?\n        \n    first of all if we see any process that is consuming heavy CPU or heavy memory that\n    is something that we can focus from here. we can find the pid and we can kill the \n    process",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "I_p_aTUoJagca70kYMxgM",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1018.9522176713419,
      "y": 33785.65138642791,
      "width": 968,
      "height": 50,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bPo",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 923049707,
      "version": 162,
      "versionNonce": 1781923390,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772802054918,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Interview Q -> In the output of your top command you are able to see something called as\n    load average what is that",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Interview Q -> In the output of your top command you are able to see something called as\n    load average what is that",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "oVEMMy_wnohlqndgTLj1f",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1098.206123921342,
      "y": 33859.34279267791,
      "width": 1089,
      "height": 800,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bPp",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2111971115,
      "version": 2485,
      "versionNonce": 2061405346,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772802054918,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "top command not only shows top processes, it also shows us the average load on \nprocessor and based on timestamp.\n\nIt shows what is average load of system on my processor, what is the average\npercentage of my processor being utilized.\n\nIn MANG interview they will ask why load average has 3 values not 1 ?\n\nwe have run top command if it will give 1 value, we know processes are constantly\nscheduling over processor like heavy process comes but lets say then it goes down\nthen smaller process comes or something like that happen and if it is only giving\none value and by chance when I am running top command my heave process is not\nscheduled on processor right now, It is somewhere down the processes which are\neasy, which are light, which are simple, which are not taking that much of CPU, those\nare scheduled for that very moment, we will feel like our processor is free because my\naverage is coming very less of top processes which are consuming my processor\n\nAt the very next second heavy process comes again this hangs our whole processor for\nnext 10 15 minutes and still I am not able to figure our whats happening with my system\nso for this reason how we will calculate load average is that it takes a average of 1 minute\n5 minute and 10 or 15 minutes something like this, 3 timestamps \nNow if in these 3 timestamps if process is not coming then we will assume that process will \nnot come now, but we will calculate average of in 1 minute whatever total load my processor\nfaced what is the average of that, in 5 minutes whatever the load it faced, what is the \naverage load it faced in 15 minutes so we get 3 values like this\n\nQ -> where top command , load average is reading it from, last 5 minute ka, last 10 minutes ka\nwhere it is reading from\nit reads it from a file where it is constantly updated and because it is updated every second, this\nhas to be done very fast, very frequent and it is kept somewhere on RAM. So where in your proc\nfolder you can read the values of load average\n-> it is reading from proc folder and exact file is load average",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "top command not only shows top processes, it also shows us the average load on \nprocessor and based on timestamp.\n\nIt shows what is average load of system on my processor, what is the average\npercentage of my processor being utilized.\n\nIn MANG interview they will ask why load average has 3 values not 1 ?\n\nwe have run top command if it will give 1 value, we know processes are constantly\nscheduling over processor like heavy process comes but lets say then it goes down\nthen smaller process comes or something like that happen and if it is only giving\none value and by chance when I am running top command my heave process is not\nscheduled on processor right now, It is somewhere down the processes which are\neasy, which are light, which are simple, which are not taking that much of CPU, those\nare scheduled for that very moment, we will feel like our processor is free because my\naverage is coming very less of top processes which are consuming my processor\n\nAt the very next second heavy process comes again this hangs our whole processor for\nnext 10 15 minutes and still I am not able to figure our whats happening with my system\nso for this reason how we will calculate load average is that it takes a average of 1 minute\n5 minute and 10 or 15 minutes something like this, 3 timestamps \nNow if in these 3 timestamps if process is not coming then we will assume that process will \nnot come now, but we will calculate average of in 1 minute whatever total load my processor\nfaced what is the average of that, in 5 minutes whatever the load it faced, what is the \naverage load it faced in 15 minutes so we get 3 values like this\n\nQ -> where top command , load average is reading it from, last 5 minute ka, last 10 minutes ka\nwhere it is reading from\nit reads it from a file where it is constantly updated and because it is updated every second, this\nhas to be done very fast, very frequent and it is kept somewhere on RAM. So where in your proc\nfolder you can read the values of load average\n-> it is reading from proc folder and exact file is load average",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "BWjSJTKuTA2sr6MNScvSj",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 863.0772176713419,
      "y": 34756.45216767791,
      "width": 77,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
