      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "When we regularily delete Yes. that is why we say whenever we are reselling our laptop or doing\nsomething like this. We should use a file shredder. What file shredder do is, it will go through\nentire sectors of our file, either it will write it with 0 or it will write it with random \nnumbers, it will rewrite entire thing with random garbage. So that it can be used again.\n\nHow can memory gets freed then?\n    Because HDD is just noting the starting pointer or ending pointer. It is just calculating that\nIt is not checking each and every sector. So if we will write something it will overwrite the\nsector.\n\nthere is format and deep formating -> if we will do deep formating it will take some time it will\noverwrite each and every sectory and put random garbage in each and every sector of partition\n but formating will not take time due to it will just delete file system table.\n\nSO this is a way if we want to delete fast just remove the pointer and memory is free to reuse due\nto that address/inode is free and free memory is calculated based on inode is free or not. If inode is\nfree writing data will overwrite that inode or address. But if we want to deep delete, there is a feature\nof deep deletion there are file shredder and everything we can go ahead and delete. So always before reselling\nlaptop or mobile do a deep formating.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "When we regularily delete Yes. that is why we say whenever we are reselling our laptop or doing\nsomething like this. We should use a file shredder. What file shredder do is, it will go through\nentire sectors of our file, either it will write it with 0 or it will write it with random \nnumbers, it will rewrite entire thing with random garbage. So that it can be used again.\n\nHow can memory gets freed then?\n    Because HDD is just noting the starting pointer or ending pointer. It is just calculating that\nIt is not checking each and every sector. So if we will write something it will overwrite the\nsector.\n\nthere is format and deep formating -> if we will do deep formating it will take some time it will\noverwrite each and every sectory and put random garbage in each and every sector of partition\n but formating will not take time due to it will just delete file system table.\n\nSO this is a way if we want to delete fast just remove the pointer and memory is free to reuse due\nto that address/inode is free and free memory is calculated based on inode is free or not. If inode is\nfree writing data will overwrite that inode or address. But if we want to deep delete, there is a feature\nof deep deletion there are file shredder and everything we can go ahead and delete. So always before reselling\nlaptop or mobile do a deep formating.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
