      "updated": 1772815786729,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Router is giving IP to all systems",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Router is giving IP to all systems",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "60gvnie-Vk9vdSS2yoLmp",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1657.1264309044911,
      "y": 40395.52872131584,
      "width": 858,
      "height": 625,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bWZ",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1250710754,
      "version": 1427,
      "versionNonce": 1717142142,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772818587073,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Lets say we are working on a company and these are our\ndev & prod systems due to these are connected in a same\nrouter(network), it might possible dev may do some changes\nin prod by mistake. So it is risky to put all of these\nin same network.\n\nthat is why we try to group ips in a way, we will constant\nsome specific bits. \n\n10.0.________.________ -> these many systems are group together -> dev subnet\n10.1.________.________ -> these many systems are group together -> prod subnet\n\nNow between these 2 groups we can set firewall rule in our Router\nthat don't allow 10.0 to communicate with 10.1\n\nthis grouping is called as subnet.\n\nthis type of subnet mast where we need to block these octets are called as\nclass based subnet mask. Here we can pick subnet mask by blocking number \nof bits like 8, 16, 24\n\n\nCIDR(Classless Inter Domain Routing) ->  Here we not restrict on octets\nwe can block any number of bits like 23 bits we can block and other\nnetwork bits will be variable.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Lets say we are working on a company and these are our\ndev & prod systems due to these are connected in a same\nrouter(network), it might possible dev may do some changes\nin prod by mistake. So it is risky to put all of these\nin same network.\n\nthat is why we try to group ips in a way, we will constant\nsome specific bits. \n\n10.0.________.________ -> these many systems are group together -> dev subnet\n10.1.________.________ -> these many systems are group together -> prod subnet\n\nNow between these 2 groups we can set firewall rule in our Router\nthat don't allow 10.0 to communicate with 10.1\n\nthis grouping is called as subnet.\n\nthis type of subnet mast where we need to block these octets are called as\nclass based subnet mask. Here we can pick subnet mask by blocking number \nof bits like 8, 16, 24\n\n\nCIDR(Classless Inter Domain Routing) ->  Here we not restrict on octets\nwe can block any number of bits like 23 bits we can block and other\nnetwork bits will be variable.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
